<h1>Envisioning Design</h1>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>The Design phase is all about creation. In creating new things, whether product or service, it can be difficult to express the fullness of our ideas verbally or in text, especially as teammates begin to dig into the ideas and try to understand them. To aid our idea expression and development, designers use non-verbal or textual communication to show their ideas and thoughts in addition to talking and/or writing about them. These alternatives include: drawing, collaging, and three dimensional model-building. There are two broad advantages to combining showing with telling:</p>

<ul>
  <li> Showing as well as telling allows vague or complex ideas can start to take shape rapidly. These concrete items, like drawings or models, retain their shape while words fly about and sometimes get lost, forgotten, or misunderstood.</li>
  <li> Making a collage, a drawing, or building a model of an idea brings the idea away from the individual into a stand-alone space so that it can be evaluated without attaching evaluation to the individual.</li>
  <li> By layering showing and telling, designers can communicate more complexity than if they stayed with either showing or telling. </li>
</ul>

    <h2>Visual Communication</h2>
    <p>Why draw your thoughts? If we have spent a lifetime reading articles and writing text and having verbal conversations, what could be the positive results of literally staring at a drawing board? We have writing skills: why start back at the
      beginning with drawing?
    </p>
      <p>In short: because drawing ideas is faster, more clear, and more actionable than just talking about them.</p>
      <br>

  <h2>Communicating Sunny-ness</h2>
