    <p>
      None of the photos in this section are actually sunny. One is a sunny looking logo; one is a photograph of a flower that is itself quite sunny (and fried egg-like), on a sunny day, while the third is a photo of a beach with some sun. <!--while the third are some words that make no literal sense (you can't walk on sunshine) but their shape and color is happy.-->So none of these things are sunny. But we can use any of these to help tell each other what we mean when we mean "sunny". Do we mean literally sunny, as in the photo of the flower and the beach? Or a reference of sunniness, like in the illustration?
    </p>

    <img src="/images/sunny_logo.svg" class="square_right" alt="sunny logo">
    <p>When meeting as a design team to start thinking of ideas for design solutions, you might say "I'm thinking it needs to be sunny." and that could be interpreted as any one of the meanings of "sunny" shown above. However, if you show an example of what you mean when you mean sunny, by showing the typeface or sketching a logo or even showing the beach, you'll be able to communicate to the team more precisely what you're thinking. This is the function of layering verbal and written communications with other forms in the design process.</p>

